ce:section.ce:para:
Graphene is a very famous 2D materials, which exhibits huge advantages as energy storage material. However, some disadvantage, such as the aggregation and restacking of graphene sheets and charge storage based on electric double layer capacitors (EDLCs) theory limit the implementation of high electrochemical performance [18]. So PPD was selected as functional agent to crosslink graphene networks by a facile hydrothermal method, then the CDs was used as fill factor to regulate the crosslinking degree of PPD for optimized functionalized 3D graphene networks in order to avoid aggregation and contribute pseudo-capacitive property. The fabrication process of functionalized 3D rGO networks decorated with PPD and CDs (rGO-PPD-CDs) is described schematically in Scheme 1. The GO, CDs and rGO-PPD-CDs were investigated by TEM (Fig. 1
                     ). As shown in Fig. 1c and d, the rGO-PPD-CDs exhibits distinct wrinkled structure which prevents aggregation of graphene sheets. Compared to the rGO-PPD-CDs, the graphene exhibits multilayer stacking state (Fig. 1a). In addition, CDs possess a uniform structure with the particle size is about 2.13 nm (Fig. 1b). Furthermore, the morphologies of rGO, rGO-PPD and rGO-PPD-CDs were investigated by SEM (Fig. 2
                     ). As shown in Fig. 2a and b, the rGO shows aggregation appearance. Obviously, the rGO-PPD shows obvious porous structure and graphene sheets also exhibits distinct wrinkled structure indicating crosslinked structure graphene sheets by PPD molecules (Fig. 2c and d) [37, 38]. It is clearly that graphene sheets reveal larger distance of the rGO-PPD-CDs due to the crosslinking degree of PPD regulated by CDs (Fig. 2e-j), and the 3D structure of rGO-PPD-CDs can be realized optimal structure for enlarging the specific surface area, facilitating rapid ion movement and promoting the electrochemical capacitance though adjusting the CDs amount [28].
